Regular Expressions

Tasks:

Either read in the data using the code below (need to install googlesheets4 library if you don’t have it) or download from this URL and put it in your project folder.

bestsellers <- read_sheet("https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1n3xKHK4-t5S73LgxOJVJWT5fMYjLj7kqmYl1LHkpk80/edit?usp=sharing")

BE SURE TO REMOVE eval=FALSE from all code sections.

  1. Find books with multiple authors (HINT: Consider the possibility of an author having “and” in their name)
bestsellers %>% 
  mutate(mult_auth = str_detect(bestsellers %>% pull(author), "\\sand\\s")) %>% 
  filter(mult_auth)
  1. Detect if the author’s first name starts with a vowel
bestsellers %>% 
  mutate(vowel = str_detect(bestsellers %>% pull(author), "^[AEIOU]")) %>% 
  filter(vowel)
  1. Change all authors with the name Alexander to Alex
bestsellers %>% 
  mutate(names = str_replace_all(author, "Alexander", "Alex"))
  1. Find books that are the second book in a series
bestsellers %>%
  mutate(series = str_detect(bestsellers %>% pull(description), 
                             pattern = "second book")) %>%
  filter(series == TRUE)
  1. Find books that are the third or fourth one in a series
bestsellers %>%
  mutate(series = str_detect(bestsellers %>% pull(description), 
                             pattern = "(third|fourth) book")) %>%
  filter(series == TRUE)
  1. Find books that are the 10th, 11th, …, or 19th book in a series
bestsellers %>%
  mutate(series = str_detect(bestsellers %>% pull(description), 
                             pattern = "1[0-9]th book")) %>%
  filter(series == TRUE)
  1. Describe in your own words how you would go about writing a regular expression for password pattern matching (ie 8 character minimum, one capital letter minimum, one lowercase letter minimum, one digit minimum, one special character minimum)

I would write out each requirement using regular expressions and try to combine them.

  1. Using a new data set, NDL_muni municipality data from the Netherlands, create a plot with two separate maps. One showing the percentage of men per municipality of the whole country, and one showing the same but faceted by province.
tmap_mode("plot")

data(NLD_muni)

NLD_muni <- NLD_muni %>% 
  mutate(perc_men = pop_men / population * 100)

m1 <- tm_shape(NLD_muni) + 
  tm_polygons("perc_men", 
              palette = 'RdYlBu')

m2 <- tm_shape(NLD_muni) +
    tm_polygons("perc_men", 
                palette = "RdYlBu") +
    tm_facets(by = "province")

tmap_arrange(m1, m2)

Data Ethics: Data visualization principles

I’m hoping that the topic for this week is a review for all of you, but it’s good to remind ourselves of these principles.

Task:

Read both short articles in Week6. Data visualization section of Calling Bulllshit. Were there any principles mentioned that you hadn’t heard of before? What graph stood out for you as “the worst”? Did any of the graphs fool you? Or were able to overcome the bad practices (don’t worry if they fool you - plenty of them have fooled me, too.)? How does practicing good data visualization principles fit in with data ethics?

Regarding the misleading axes article, I was surprised by pretty much all of them because. Aside from the first one about bar charts should include 0, the other ones felt so blatantly wrong that it didn’t even occur to me that people would make those mistakes (intentionally or not). The principles surrounding the bar charts from both articles were quite illuminating because I had never thought about the relative scale or proportion of the bars before. To be honest I would have been fooled by the featured bar charts because visually they looked quite nice. The graph I found most interesting was the one about common causes of death in the changing denominator section. I could interpret it fine but I guess it was because I understood right away that the figures were percentages but I could see how misleading it could be. I think practicing good data viz principles is crucial because visualizing data is one way to communicate the data or the data analysis and is intended to reach a wider audience. Graphs visualizing the same data can tell wildly different stories depending on how they were created. Thus, they need to be represent their data truthfully and in the appropriate context as we don’t want to unintentionally warp the narrative or skew public opinion.
